7. Suppose the logs are empty. The container exits immediately, and docker logs doesn't show anything useful. What would you do next?
Ans 
If docker logs is empty, I would first use docker inspect to verify the runtime configuration, such as the command, entrypoint, environment variables, mounted volumes, and networking. I would also compare the image and configuration with the last known working version to identify any recent changes.

If I still couldn't determine the issue, I would start the image with an overridden entrypoint, such as /bin/sh, to keep the container running. That allows me to inspect the filesystem, verify environment variables, check permissions, and manually run the application to identify why it exits immediately. 
docker run -it --entrypoint /bin/sh <image>
Now the container stays alive with a shell, allowing you to inspect:
Files
Environment variables (env)
Permissions (ls -l)
Mounted volumes
Application binaries
Configuration files
This is one of the most common production debugging techniques.

