9. What is the difference between CMD and ENTRYPOINT? When would you use each?
Ans 
docker run ubuntu echo hello
CMD: Default command or default arguments
ENTRYPOINT: The executable that must always run
CMD specifies the default command or default arguments that are executed when a container starts. Users can easily override the CMD by providing a command after the image name in docker run.
ENTRYPOINT, on the other hand, defines the main executable that should always run when the container starts. It is typically used for the application's primary process and is not overridden by simply providing a command. Instead, any command supplied to docker run is passed as arguments to the ENTRYPOINT. If required, the ENTRYPOINT itself can be overridden using the --entrypoint option.

A common pattern is to use ENTRYPOINT for the executable and CMD for its default arguments."

