10. What is a Docker layer? Why does Docker use layers, and what are the benefits?
Ans
A Docker layer is a read-only filesystem layer created by most Dockerfile instructions. Docker stacks these layers together to build the final image.

Docker uses layers to improve build performance, optimize storage, and reduce network usage. During a rebuild, Docker reuses cached layers until it encounters a changed instruction. That instruction and all subsequent layers are rebuilt, while the earlier unchanged layers are reused.

Layers are also shared between images, which reduces disk usage, and when pushing an image to a registry such as Docker Hub or Amazon ECR, Docker uploads only the layers that are not already present."
If two images share the same base image, Docker stores the common layers only once.

Example:

Image A
---------
Ubuntu
Python
App A

Image B
---------
Ubuntu
Python
App B

Docker doesn't store Ubuntu and Python twice.
