11. What is the difference between docker pull and docker run?
Ans docker pull is used only to download an image from a container registry, such as Docker Hub, into the local image store. It does not create or start any containers.

docker run, on the other hand, creates and starts a new container from an image. If the required image is not available locally, Docker automatically pulls it from the registry before creating the container.

For example, after running docker pull nginx, there are no containers—only the image is available locally. Running docker run nginx creates one container. Running docker run nginx again creates another new container, so there are now two independent containers created from the same image.
Docker contacts the registry and checks whether your local image matches the remote image for the latest tag.

If your local image is already up to date, Docker reuses the existing layers and downloads nothing.
If newer layers exist, Docker downloads only the missing or changed layers.
It does not blindly "update" the image every time.

