4. What is the difference between docker stop and docker kill?
Ans "docker stop performs a graceful shutdown by sending a SIGTERM signal to the container's main process. This allows the application to complete ongoing work, close files, release resources, and shut down cleanly. Docker waits for a timeout period before forcefully terminating the process if it does not exit. docker kill, on the other hand, immediately terminates the container by sending a SIGKILL signal by default. It does not allow the application to perform cleanup. In production, I always prefer docker stop. I use docker kill only when a container becomes unresponsive or fails to stop gracefully."

