7. How would you restructure the Dockerfile layers to cache the Maven dependencies locally inside the Docker build cache, so that re-downloads only happen when pom.xml changes?

Ans
If you write COPY pom.xml pom.xml and then RUN mvn clean package without copying the src/ folder, the Maven build will crash with: "Source directory does not exist" Because mvn package compiles the Java code. You haven't given it any code to compile yet! The Production-Grade Fix (Memorize this exact pattern): In enterprise Dockerfiles (especially for SBI/Java apps), we use Maven's dependency:go-offline goal. This downloads all your dependencies from pom.xml into the local Maven cache WITHOUT needing the source code. Correct Dockerfile snippet: dockerfile # 1. Copy ONLY the dependency definition files first COPY pom.xml /app/pom.xml # 2. Run a special Maven command to download ALL dependencies without compiling RUN mvn dependency:go-offline # 3. NOW copy the entire source code (this invalidates the cache only when code changes) COPY src /app/src # 4. Finally, compile and package (it uses the cached dependencies from step 2) RUN mvn clean package Why this cracks the interview: Step 2 downloads all 100MB of dependencies into Docker's layer cache. When you change a line of Java code in src/, Step 1 and Step 2 are reused (cache hit). Only Step 3 and Step 4 re-run, taking ~10 seconds instead of 5 minutes. When you change pom.xml, Step 2 re-runs and redownloads deps.

# 1. Copy ONLY the dependency definition files first
COPY pom.xml /app/pom.xml
# 2. Run a special Maven command to download ALL dependencies without compiling
RUN mvn dependency:go-offline
# 3. NOW copy the entire source code (this invalidates the cache only when code changes)
COPY src /app/src
# 4. Finally, compile and package (it uses the cached dependencies from step 2)
RUN mvn clean package

