10. Your image is 400MB, which is too bloated. Look at these 4 lines. What is the main problem with splitting them like this, and how would you rewrite these exact lines to drastically reduce the image size?"

Ans: "The problem with splitting them into four separate RUN commands is two-fold.
First, each RUN creates a separate layer in the final image, which bloats the size. But the bigger, more dangerous issue is the stale cache problem. If I run apt-get update in its own layer, Docker caches that layer. Three weeks later, if I modify the second line to install a new package, Docker reuses the cached apt-get update layer from three weeks ago. That outdated package list might not have the new package I need, or worse, it could return a 404 because the URLs have changed, breaking my build entirely.

The fix is to combine everything into a single RUN command using &&, and to clean up in the same layer:

dockerfile
RUN apt-get update && apt-get install -y --no-install-recommends \
    curl \
    netcat \
    vim \
    && apt-get clean \
    && rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/*
I use --no-install-recommends to avoid pulling in unnecessary suggested packages, which shrinks the image size. Then I run apt-get clean and rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/* to delete the downloaded package files. And critically, I do all of this inside the same RUN command, because if I delete the files in a separate RUN layer, the previous layer still contains the files, so the image size doesn't actually shrink. This single-layer approach gives me a smaller, more secure, and cache-friendly image.

11. What is the difference between COPY and ADD? In this specific scenario (copying a local requirements.txt), which one should you use, and why?"

The difference is that COPY is simple and predictable. It just copies files and directories from my local build context directly into the container's filesystem. Period. No magic. ADD, on the other hand, has two extra 'magic' features: It can copy files from remote URLs (like ADD https://example.com/file.zip /tmp/). It can automatically extract local compressed tarballs (like ADD package.tar.gz /app/ which unpacks it). For copying my local requirements.txt, I would always use COPY and never ADD. Here is why: It's the official Docker best practice. The Docker documentation explicitly recommends COPY over ADD unless I specifically need the URL or auto-extraction features. Security: If I accidentally use ADD with a remote URL, I'm downloading code from the internet during the build. For a banking client like SBI, that's a security risk. It bypasses our internal artifact repositories. We want total control over where our code comes from. Predictability: COPY is transparent. Every engineer knows exactly what it does. ADD auto-extracting a tarball can cause surprises if you didn't intend for it to unpack. So, to summarize, in this exact scenario—copying requirements.txt—I use COPY. I only switch to ADD if I intentionally need to download a remote file or unpack a tarball during the build, which is almost never in a production microservice setup."

12. What is the difference between ENV and ARG in a Dockerfile?
The difference is that ARG is a build-time variable, and ENV is a runtime environment variable that persists inside the running container. - ARG is only available during docker build. I can pass it in with --build-arg. Once the image is built, ARG values are gone. They don't exist when the container runs. - ENV sets an environment variable that stays inside the container. The running application can read it at runtime.If I use ARG instead, I cannot override it at docker run. ARG is only for build time. To pass JVM arguments at runtime, I must use ENV or the -e flag.

13. Problem: The image is 700MB because it includes the entire JDK, Maven, source code, and all dependencies. The SBI cloud team is complaining about storage costs in ECR.
Question:
What is a multi-stage build in Docker?
Rewrite this Dockerfile using multi-stage to produce a final image that is < 200MB. Show me the exact Dockerfile.
Ans: A multi-stage build uses multiple FROM statements in a single Dockerfile. Each stage can have its own base image. I can copy artifacts from an earlier stage into a later stage, and the earlier stages' layers are discarded in the final image.
Here is the production-ready multi-stage Dockerfile for our SBI Spring Boot application:
dockerfile
# Stage 1: Build stage (uses full JDK + Maven)
FROM maven:3.8-openjdk-17 AS builder
WORKDIR /app
# Copy only pom.xml first for dependency caching
COPY pom.xml .
RUN mvn dependency:go-offline
# Copy source code and build the JAR
COPY src/ ./src/
RUN mvn clean package -DskipTests
# Stage 2: Runtime stage (uses only lightweight JRE)
FROM eclipse-temurin:17-jre-alpine
WORKDIR /app
# Copy the JAR from the builder stage
COPY --from=builder /app/target/app.jar /app/app.jar
# Create non-root user for security
RUN addgroup -S appgroup && adduser -S appuser -G appgroup
RUN chown -R appuser:appgroup /app
USER appuser

EXPOSE 8080
ENTRYPOINT ["java", "-jar", "app.jar"]
Now the final image is ~180MB because it only contains the JRE and the JAR, not Maven, the JDK, or the source code. The builder stage layers are never included in the final image."

14. Can I use a different base image for each stage? What if I want to use amazoncorretto:17-alpine in the second stage instead?" Also: The interviewer adds: "What happens to the builder stage layers after the image is built? Are they stored on my machine?"

Compatibility note: When I use different base images, the build artifacts must be compatible. For example, if I build a native binary in a golang:alpine stage, I can copy that binary to a scratch (empty) stage. But if I build a JAR in a maven:openjdk-17 stage, I must copy it to a stage that has a JRE (like eclipse-temurin:17-jre-alpine). I can't copy a JAR to a scratch image because Java isn't installed there to run it.

Cache behavior: Yes, the builder stage layers are stored locally. They're not in the final image, but they're cached as separate layers. This means the next time I build, Docker reuses the cached mvn dependency:go-offline layer, drastically speeding up the build. If I want to clean these up, I use docker builder prune to free disk space."

